default5.1
default              
defaultAt the heart of our case are 
defaultthree 
defaultarguments around the better use of resou
defaultrces
default, and potential new sources of funding,
default that devolution will bring.  
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default              
defaultFirst, we expect that in a 
defaultP
defaultartnership 
defaultwith DfT 
defaultthat evolves 
defaulttowards a devolved railway that responsibility for resource allocation and funding will transfer over time to the North.  B
defaultecause of the challenge created 
defaultby 
defaultdeveloping a
default growing 
defaultrailway that
default 
defaultsupports 
defaultdeliver
defaulty
default of regional 
defaulteconomic outcomes, 
defaultthe North 
defaultwill 
defaultbe very strongly incentivised to find ways of making the railway more efficient 
defaultin 
defaultdelivering 
defaultthese
default outcomes. 
default 
defaultThis includes a greater management focus on performance, through a better understanding of what matters to passengers (and businesses) locally.  
defaultOver the past 15 years nationally-run franchising has delivered very little impact on industry efficiency in the North.  In part this is because nationally-inspired efficiencies were often developed in isolation from the local benefits that might be brough
defaultt about through them.  
defaultThe partnership work between DfT and the North must 
defaultact to drive such efficiencies and recycle their benefits into a railway that promotes the economy of the North and provides a better railway.  
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default              
defaultSecond, 
defaulta stronger role for northern authorities in the railway 
defaultwill deliver better integration of 
default(a) 
defaultdecision making
default,
default and 
default(b) transport planning and 
defaultnetworks
default.  
defaultNationally-led franchising has tended to favour development of those services that have least impact o
defaultn the direct transport budget.  Whilst this is a financially pragmatic short-term approach it means that some services which have a high economic impact can be neglected.  By integrating rail into wider transport networks and ‘places’ 
defaultthe North 
defaultcan make th
defaulte railway 
defaulta more coherent part of wider transport systems, and 
defaultbetter
default for passengers
default.  
default&#xa0;
default5.4
default              
defaultThird, a railway 
defaultwith strong “local ownership” 
defaultis more likely to be able to secure funds for further development.  The Rail North work on a Long Term Rail Strategy
default has already catalysed work on sub-regional priorities; this has been complementary to work by LEPs and L
defaultocal Transport Boards
default in prioritising recently devolved funds 
defaultat a sub-regional level 
default(e.g. transport funds, city deals, local transport block funds an
defaultd local growth funds). Together this work will ensure that 
defaultbusiness 
defaultcases for greater investment in transport are better founded, and hence it is more likely that local funds will (a) be spent on better value transport interventions, and (b) be more confid
defaultently applied by local agencies.  Furthermore where such priorities coincide with the wider aims of the Long Term Rail Strategy there will be a stronger case to apply any surpluses Rail North Ltd may gain from any profit or revenue share arrangements it ha
defaults in place with the train operator, thus multiplying the impact of scarce locally-derived funds.  
